                the contrivance of it on the inſide was full of Seats and ranges of Pillars, and on the outſide in the Roof or covering of it was made from one point at top with a great many bendings, all ſhelving downward; they ſay that it was ſo made after the Copy and in imitation of the King of Perſia's Pavilion, and this by Pericles his order likewiſe: Upon which occaſion Cratinus again in his Comedy called The Thracian Women plays upon him with rallery thus;
